      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "During intense HIIT intervals, your muscles rely on anaerobic glycolysis to generate energy faster than oxygen can be supplied, leading to the breakdown of pyruvate into lactate. This lactate is actually a useful fuel source that is cleared by the liver within 10–40 minutes after exercise through the Cori cycle. While older terminology referred to it as \"lactic acid,\" it is technically a neutral molecule that only forms acid when combined with protons, which usually deplete in the same timeframe as lactate production ceases.",
